---
import BaseLayout from '../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import ToolPageCta from '../../components/ToolPageCta.astro';
import FaqSection from '../../components/FaqSection.astro';

const faq = [
  { question: "What is the difference between code coverage and mutation score?", answer: "Code coverage tells you which lines of code were executed during tests. It says nothing about whether your assertions actually verify the behaviour of that code. Mutation score measures how many of Stryker's artificial bugs (mutants) your tests caught and killed. A test that covers a line but has no assertions will show 100% coverage but 0% mutation score. Mutation score is a much stronger indicator of test quality." },
  { question: "What is a mutant in Stryker?", answer: "A mutant is a small, targeted change Stryker makes to your source code — one at a time — to see if your tests detect it. Examples: changing && to ||, flipping > to >=, replacing a return value with undefined, or deleting a conditional block. Stryker runs the full test suite against each mutant. A 'killed' mutant means at least one test failed, proving those tests guard that behaviour. A 'survived' mutant means no test caught the change — a gap in your suite." },
  { question: "How do I configure Stryker with Vitest?", answer: "Install the Vitest runner: npm install --save-dev @stryker-mutator/core @stryker-mutator/vitest-runner. In stryker.config.mjs, set testRunner: 'vitest' and coverageAnalysis: 'perTest'. For large projects, add disableTypeChecks: true to significantly speed up runs. Stryker will use your existing vitest.config.ts automatically." },
  { question: "What mutation score threshold should I aim for?", answer: "For business-critical code (payment logic, auth, data validation), aim for 80%+. For general application code, 60-70% is a realistic goal. Scores below 40% typically indicate tests that were written to satisfy coverage requirements rather than to verify behaviour. Do not chase 100% — some mutants are inherently equivalent (the mutation produces the same behaviour) and are not worth the test complexity." },
  { question: "How do I ignore specific mutants in Stryker?", answer: "Use the mutate config to exclude files: mutate: ['src/**/*.ts', '!src/**/*.spec.ts']. To ignore specific mutant types project-wide, use the excludedMutations option: ['StringLiteral', 'BlockStatement']. For fine-grained ignoring, add a Stryker comment in source code: // Stryker disable next-line ArithmeticOperator. Use ignoring sparingly — it should document why a mutant is intentionally untested, not cover up gaps." },
  { question: "How does Stryker help find untested edge cases?", answer: "Stryker systematically mutates boundary conditions (changing > to >= or <), boolean operators (&&, ||), null checks, and return values. Surviving mutants in boundary condition code reveal tests that pass with one value but would fail with the edge case one step away. This is exactly where off-by-one bugs and null pointer errors hide. Running Stryker on a function like validateAge(age) will quickly reveal whether your tests check the boundary (18, 17, 19) or only the happy path." },
];
---

<BaseLayout
  title="Stryker Mutation Testing: Measure Real Test Quality Guide"
  description="Stryker mutation testing guide for JavaScript/TypeScript: understand mutation score, configure stryker.config, run with Jest/Vitest, interpret reports, and improve test suite quality."
  tool="Stryker, mutation testing, mutation score, JavaScript testing, test quality, Jest, Vitest"
  faq={faq}
>
  <script type="application/ld+json" set:html={JSON.stringify({
    "@context": "https://schema.org",
    "@type": "WebPage",
    "name": "Stryker Mutation Testing: Measure Real Test Quality Guide",
    "url": "https://devplaybook.cc/tools/stryker-mutation-testing",
    "description": "Stryker mutation testing guide for JavaScript/TypeScript: understand mutation score, configure stryker.config, run with Jest/Vitest, interpret reports, and improve test suite quality.",
  })} />

  <h1 class="text-3xl font-bold mb-2">Stryker Mutation Testing: Measure Real Test Quality</h1>
  <p class="text-text-muted mb-6">Code coverage tells you which lines were run. Mutation testing tells you whether your tests actually verify the code's behaviour. Stryker introduces hundreds of tiny bugs into your codebase one at a time and checks if your tests catch them. If a test suite scores 95% coverage but only 40% mutation score, the tests are not doing their job.</p>

  <div class="flex items-center gap-3 mb-6 text-sm text-text-muted flex-wrap">
    <span class="flex items-center gap-1.5"><span class="text-green-500">✓</span> Reveals gaps code coverage hides</span>
    <span class="flex items-center gap-1.5"><span class="text-green-500">✓</span> Works with Jest, Vitest, Mocha, Jasmine</span>
    <span class="flex items-center gap-1.5"><span class="text-green-500">✓</span> HTML report with killed/survived breakdown</span>
    <span class="flex items-center gap-1.5"><span class="text-green-500">✓</span> Configurable thresholds for CI gates</span>
  </div>

  <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold mt-8 mb-3">What Is Mutation Testing?</h2>
  <p class="text-text-muted mb-4">Mutation testing is a technique where automated tooling makes small, deliberate changes (mutations) to your source code and checks whether your tests detect each change. If the test suite still passes after a mutation, the mutant "survived" — meaning your tests have a blind spot at that exact point in the code.</p>
  <p class="text-text-muted mb-6">The mutation score is: (killed mutants / total mutants) × 100. A score of 75% means 25% of the artificial bugs slipped past your tests undetected.</p>

  <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold mt-8 mb-3">How Stryker Works</h2>
  <div class="overflow-x-auto mb-6">
    <table class="w-full text-sm border-collapse">
      <thead>
        <tr class="bg-gray-800 text-white">
          <th class="border border-gray-700 px-4 py-2 text-left">Mutant Status</th>
          <th class="border border-gray-700 px-4 py-2 text-left">Meaning</th>
          <th class="border border-gray-700 px-4 py-2 text-left">Action</th>
        </tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody class="text-text-muted">
        <tr>
          <td class="border border-gray-700 px-4 py-2">Killed</td>
          <td class="border border-gray-700 px-4 py-2">A test failed — bug was caught</td>
          <td class="border border-gray-700 px-4 py-2">Good, no action needed</td>
        </tr>
        <tr class="bg-gray-800/30">
          <td class="border border-gray-700 px-4 py-2">Survived</td>
          <td class="border border-gray-700 px-4 py-2">All tests passed — bug escaped</td>
          <td class="border border-gray-700 px-4 py-2">Write a test that catches this</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td class="border border-gray-700 px-4 py-2">No Coverage</td>
          <td class="border border-gray-700 px-4 py-2">No test even ran this code</td>
          <td class="border border-gray-700 px-4 py-2">Add coverage first</td>
        </tr>
        <tr class="bg-gray-800/30">
          <td class="border border-gray-700 px-4 py-2">Timeout</td>
          <td class="border border-gray-700 px-4 py-2">Mutant caused an infinite loop</td>
          <td class="border border-gray-700 px-4 py-2">Counts as killed</td>
        </tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
  </div>

  <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold mt-8 mb-3">Installation and stryker.config.mjs</h2>
  <pre class="bg-gray-900 border border-gray-700 rounded-lg p-4 overflow-x-auto text-sm mb-4"><code class="text-green-400">npm install --save-dev @stryker-mutator/core @stryker-mutator/jest-runner
# or for Vitest:
npm install --save-dev @stryker-mutator/core @stryker-mutator/vitest-runner</code></pre>
  <pre class="bg-gray-900 border border-gray-700 rounded-lg p-4 overflow-x-auto text-sm mb-6"><code class="text-green-400">// stryker.config.mjs
export default &#123;
  testRunner: 'jest',           // or 'vitest'
  coverageAnalysis: 'perTest',  // fastest: only re-run relevant tests
  mutate: ['src/**/*.ts', '!src/**/*.spec.ts'],
  reporters: ['html', 'clear-text', 'progress'],
  thresholds: &#123; high: 80, low: 60, break: 50 &#125;,
  disableTypeChecks: true,      // speeds up runs significantly
&#125;;</code></pre>

  <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold mt-8 mb-3">Running Stryker</h2>
  <pre class="bg-gray-900 border border-gray-700 rounded-lg p-4 overflow-x-auto text-sm mb-6"><code class="text-green-400"># Run mutation tests:
npx stryker run

# Run only on changed files (faster in development):
npx stryker run --mutate "src/auth/**/*.ts"

# Output: reports/mutation/mutation.html — open in browser for full report</code></pre>

  <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold mt-8 mb-3">Common Surviving Mutant Types</h2>
  <div class="overflow-x-auto mb-6">
    <table class="w-full text-sm border-collapse">
      <thead>
        <tr class="bg-gray-800 text-white">
          <th class="border border-gray-700 px-4 py-2 text-left">Mutant Type</th>
          <th class="border border-gray-700 px-4 py-2 text-left">Example Change</th>
          <th class="border border-gray-700 px-4 py-2 text-left">What to Add</th>
        </tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody class="text-text-muted">
        <tr>
          <td class="border border-gray-700 px-4 py-2">Boundary condition</td>
          <td class="border border-gray-700 px-4 py-2">age &gt; 18 → age &gt;= 18</td>
          <td class="border border-gray-700 px-4 py-2">Test with value 18</td>
        </tr>
        <tr class="bg-gray-800/30">
          <td class="border border-gray-700 px-4 py-2">Boolean flip</td>
          <td class="border border-gray-700 px-4 py-2">isActive &amp;&amp; isValid → isActive || isValid</td>
          <td class="border border-gray-700 px-4 py-2">Test where one condition is false</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td class="border border-gray-700 px-4 py-2">Return value</td>
          <td class="border border-gray-700 px-4 py-2">return result → return undefined</td>
          <td class="border border-gray-700 px-4 py-2">Assert the return value explicitly</td>
        </tr>
        <tr class="bg-gray-800/30">
          <td class="border border-gray-700 px-4 py-2">String literal</td>
          <td class="border border-gray-700 px-4 py-2">'error' → ''</td>
          <td class="border border-gray-700 px-4 py-2">Assert error message content</td>
        </tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
  </div>

  <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold mt-8 mb-3">Mutation Score Thresholds</h2>
  <p class="text-text-muted mb-6">The thresholds config sets three values. high (default 80): scores at or above are shown in green. low (default 60): scores below are shown in red. break (default null): if set, Stryker exits with a non-zero code below this threshold, blocking CI. Set break: 50 as a minimum quality gate, and aim to push toward 70-80% over time as you improve your test suite.</p>

  <ToolPageCta />
  <FaqSection faq={faq} />
</BaseLayout>
